# TGS Flow Pilot

## Overview

TGS Flow is a workflow that helps teams do two things:

1. Generate Jira compliant backlog items from requirements, solution documents, meeting notes, and other planning artifacts
2. Reconcile GitHub engineering activity back into Jira so work in progress reflects actual execution

This pilot is designed to validate the end to end workflow in a controlled rollout before broader expansion.

## Pilot Goals

The pilot is focused on proving that teams can:

* Turn planning artifacts into usable Jira backlog items
* Assign work to engineers using those backlog items
* Have engineering activity reflected back into Jira during execution
* Reduce manual Jira update effort
* Improve visibility into what engineering work is actually happening

## Pilot Scope

This pilot covers two supported paths:

### Path A: TGS Flow VS Code Extension

Use the TGS Flow repo and VS Code extension workflow for backlog generation and GitHub to Jira reconciliation.

### Path B: Claude Jira CLI Path

Some participants may use the Claude Jira CLI path being supported by the parallel R2E effort.

For CLI related support, route questions to the designated CLI support lead.

## Pilot Timeline

### Sprint 1: Onboarding and Validation

**Dates:** March 19 to April 1

#### Objective

Get each pilot participant and their required engineering support set up successfully.

#### Expected Outcomes

Each participating team should:

* Install and configure the required tooling
* Run an initial test successfully
* Identify the real use case they will run in Sprint 2
* Confirm who on their team needs access and setup
* Validate that their setup works end to end

#### Minimum Success Criteria for Sprint 1

A participant is considered ready for Sprint 2 when they have:

* Access to the repo and required tools
* Completed setup successfully
* Generated a test backlog from a source document or notes
* Confirmed who will execute the engineering work in Sprint 2
* Verified that all required team members for that use case are also set up

### Sprint 2: Real Use Case Execution

**Dates:** April 2 to April 15

#### Objective

Run one real business use case per participating team through the workflow.

#### Expected Outcomes

Each team should:

* Use a real requirements or solution artifact
* Generate backlog items from that artifact
* Assign work to the appropriate team members
* Execute the work through the sprint
* Validate that Jira reflects work in progress as engineering activity happens
* Share feedback on friction points, gaps, and improvements

#### End of Sprint 2

At the end of Sprint 2, each team should be able to demonstrate:

* The source artifact used
* The generated backlog
* The resulting Jira tickets
* The engineers involved
* The resulting Jira updates during execution
* What worked, what did not, and what should change

